Bezier Curves and Surfaces

Task 1

(a) De Casteljau's algorithm is a recursive method used to evaluate Bézier curves. The algorithm recursively interpolates between every adjacent pair of points, reducing their number by one in each step. The final value is a point on the Bézier curve at a specific t

Each point is given by,

Vector2D newPoint((1 - t) * b0.x + t * b1.x, (1 - t) * b0.y + t * b1.y)

​ where b0 and b1 are an adjacent pair of points:

Repeat the process until the size of the points vector is one.

Task 2

(a)

To extend De Casteljau's algorithm to Bézier surfaces, we can apply the algorithm in two directions, first along one axis and then evaluate along another axis. This evaluation method ensures the evaluation of Bézier surfaces by evaluating a grid of control points (so instead of having only the parameter (t), we have the parameters (u, v) in the context of a Bézier surface).

Implementation Details:

For the evaluateStep function, this function evaluates just one step of De Casteljau’s algorithm by linearly interpolating between each pair of adjacent points to get closer to the final Bézier curve.

evaluate1D: This function ensures we can obtain the result of the point on the Bézier curve when the parameter is (t). It recursively calls the evaluateStep function until the size of the vector is one (meaning we’ve successfully finished our evaluation).

The final evaluate function requires us to evaluate the intermediate points (which are also on the Bézier surface) along one axis (we use the (u)-axis in our implementation). Next, we treat these intermediate points as control points for a final Bézier curve on the (v)-axis, and we call evaluate1D again to interpolate the values.

By doing this two-step process, we're able to evaluate the Bézier surface from the set of control points.

Triangle Meshes and Half-Edge Data Structure

Task 3

(a) To implement area-weighted vertex normals, we first retrieve the half-edge associated with a given edge using the halfedge() function. We then initialize a vector, weighted_normal, to zero. Next, we obtain the coordinates of the three vertices of the current triangle using the following code snippet:

Vector3D v0_pos = h_copy->vertex()->position;
Vector3D v1_pos = h_copy->next()->vertex()->position;
Vector3D v2_pos = h_copy->next()->next()->vertex()->position;

Following this, we calculate the normal vector of the current surface by performing a cross product of the two edge vectors. The magnitude of this vector is proportional to the area of the triangle, given that A = 1/2 ||n||. We then add this surface normal vector to the weighted_normal vector.

Next, we traverse all triangles incident to the current vertex, which can be achieved through either h->next()->next()->twin() or h->twin()->next().

Finally, if the norm of weighted_normal is not zero, we normalize this vector. The result is an area-weighted vertex normal.

Task 6

(a) In this loop subdivision algorithm, we first recalculate the position for each vertex, including both the newly created vertices and the original ones.

We begin by iterating over all vertices and assigning new weights to each. We use the degree() function to retrieve each vertex's degree and calculate the value of u, handling the special case where a vertex's degree is three. We weight all adjacent vertices and the vertex itself. These values are assigned at the end of the process to the vertex if it is not newly created.

Additionally, we iterate through all edges and assign a new weighted average for the newly created midpoint of the edge. For the adjacent points, a and b, we assign a weight of 3/8, and for points c and d, we assign 1/8. We then store this information in the new position of the edges. Thus, when we run the split algorithm, we can use this position information for the newly created vertex.

Finally, we need to split and flip the edges. We split all original edges (we avoid splitting the newly created edges to prevent an endless loop). Since every original edge is represented by two edges after splitting, we only mark the edges adjacent to the original edges as newly created. Then, if an edge is newly created and its two vertices include one newly created and one original vertex, we flip the edge.

After updating all vertex position information from the new positions, our upsampling algorithm is complete.

(b) After performing several iterations, sharp corners in the mesh become smoother and rounder with each iteration. This smoothing effect is due to the weighted average of the vertex positions. However, recursive subdivisions may cause asymmetries in the mesh, which could be due to numerical precision issues. However, pre-splitting some edges could mitigate this issue [will be discussed in Part C later]. ￼

(c)

By pre-splitting each edge on every face of the cube, we can increase the mesh density uniformly. This initial uniform density will help make the subsequent subdivisions more stable and lead to a more symmetrical upsampling result.
